      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome Back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's great to meet you. Before I dive into the plan, I just want to say — the consistency you've shown over these past two weeks is genuinely impressive. Six sessions, no missed days, pacing yourself carefully, and listening to your foot throughout. That kind of discipline during a return-from-injury phase is exactly what separates runners who come back stronger from those who re-injure. You've earned this next step.\n\nNow let me walk you through what I've built for you, and why.\n\n---\n\n## A Few Things Worth Knowing First\n\nYour physiotherapist has cleared you for **20 minutes of easy running only** — no speed work yet. So this plan works entirely within that boundary. Your training paces come from your pre-injury 10K of 44:00 (VDOT 46.5), which gives us an easy pace range of **5:24–5:58/km**. Right now, I'd suggest staying at the **comfortable end of that range (5:58/km)** — your fitness has likely softened a little during the layoff, and protecting the foot matters far more than hitting a pace target.\n\nOne thing I want to be transparent about: **your current weekly volume is around 9–10 km across 3 runs.** The 10% weekly progression rule means we build slowly and deliberately. That might feel frustratingly gradual — but it's the reason this plan has a real chance of sticking.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture: 8-Week Return-to-Running Plan\n\nThis plan has **two phases**:\n\n- **Phase 1 (Weeks 1–4): Consolidation & Careful Build** — Establish consistent, pain-free running. Duration increases gently. Walking breaks remain available whenever needed.\n- **Phase 2 (Weeks 5–8): Confidence & Foundation** — Extend your longest run toward 30 minutes, build weekly volume, and prepare for a conversation with your physio about what comes next.\n\n**Deload weeks occur at Weeks 4 and 8** — volume drops back intentionally. This isn't losing ground; it's when your body actually absorbs the training.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1: Consolidation & Careful Build (Weeks 1–4)\n\n### Week 1 *(~10 km total | Baseline)*\n*You've essentially been here already — this week locks in the pattern.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks if any foot discomfort |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 18 min | ~3.0 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks if any foot discomfort |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks if any foot discomfort |\n\n**Weekly total: ~9.8 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 2 *(~10.5 km total | +5%)*\n*Small step up in two sessions. Saturday stays capped at 20 min per physio clearance.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | Slight step up from 18 min |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n\n**Weekly total: ~10.2 km**\n\n> \uD83D\uDCAC **Coaching note:** Once all three runs feel consistently comfortable at 20 minutes with no foot response, that's your signal to check back in with your physio about extending beyond 20 minutes. That conversation is the gateway to Phase 2.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3 *(~10.5 km total | Consolidation)*\n*Same volume as Week 2. The goal here is consistency and confidence, not progression.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n\n**Weekly total: ~10.2 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 4 *(~9 km total | Deload \uD83D\uDD04)*\n*Intentional step back. Your tendons and connective tissue adapt more slowly than your cardiovascular system — this week is doing real work, even when it doesn't feel like it.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min | ~2.5 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks welcome |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min | ~2.5 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks welcome |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n\n**Weekly total: ~8.4 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Confidence & Foundation (Weeks 5–8)\n\n> ⚠️ **Phase 2 assumes your physiotherapist has cleared you to run beyond 20 minutes.** If that clearance hasn't come through, Phase 2 simply continues the Week 3 pattern until it does — and that's completely fine. The plan adapts to your body, not the other way around.\n\n---\n\n### Week 5 *(~12 km total | First extension)*\n*Saturday's long run extends to 25 minutes — the first time you'll go beyond your current cap. Tuesday and Thursday stay at 20 min to keep total load manageable.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:45–5:58/km | Slight pace range opens up |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:45–5:58/km | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 25 min | ~4.3 km | 5:58/km | Walk breaks if any foot response |\n\n**Weekly total: ~11.1 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 6 *(~13 km total | Building)*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 22 min | ~3.7 km | 5:45–5:58/km | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:45–5:58/km | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 28 min | ~4.7 km | 5:58/km | |\n\n**Weekly total: ~11.8 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 7 *(~14 km total | Strongest week so far)*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 25 min | ~4.2 km | 5:30–5:58/km | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 22 min | ~3.7 km | 5:45–5:58/km | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 30 min | ~5.0 km | 5:58/km | First 30-min run — a real milestone |\n\n**Weekly total: ~12.9 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 8 *(~12 km total | Deload & Reflect \uD83D\uDD04)*\n*Pull back, consolidate, and take stock. This is also a natural checkpoint for a physio review and a conversation about what comes next — whether that's introducing speed work, extending the long run further, or setting a race goal.*\n\n| Day | Session | Duration | Distance | Pace | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min | ~3.4 km | 5:58/km | |\n| Saturday | Easy Run (Long) | 25 min | ~4.3 km | 5:58/km | |\n\n**Weekly total: ~11.1 km**\n\n---\n\n## A Few Principles Woven Into This Plan\n\n**Why so much easy pace?**\nPlantar fasciitis involves the connective tissue of the foot — and connective tissue adapts *much* more slowly than muscle or cardiovascular fitness. Running easy keeps load on the foot manageable while still building the aerobic base you'll need later. Pushing pace now risks a setback that could cost months, not days.\n\n**Why no redistribution of missed sessions?**\nIf you miss a run, it stays missed. Adding mileage to other days to \"make up\" for it increases injury risk without meaningful fitness benefit. One skipped session in an 8-week plan is noise — it won't define your outcome.\n\n**Why walking breaks?**\nThey're not a sign of weakness — they're a load-management tool. A 20-minute run/walk puts less cumulative stress on the plantar fascia than 20 minutes of continuous running. Use them freely, especially on days when the foot feels stiff early.\n\n**Why deload weeks?**\nYour body doesn't adapt *during* hard weeks — it adapts *after* them, during recovery. Deload weeks are when the training from the previous three weeks actually becomes fitness.\n\n---\n\n## Your Paces (For Reference)\n\n| Type | Pace Range | When Used |\n|---|---|---|\n| Easy (current) | 5:58/km | All runs now |\n| Easy (full range) | 5:24–5:58/km | Phase 2 as comfort grows |\n| Threshold | 4:29/km | Not until physio clears speed work |\n| Interval | 4:12/km | Not until physio clears speed work |\n\n---\n\n## What Happens After Week 8?\n\nBy the end of this plan, you'll have 8 weeks of consistent, pain-free running under your feet, a 30-minute long run, and a solid aerobic foundation to build from. That's the launchpad for a proper base-building block — and eventually, a return to chasing that 44:00 10K (and beyond).\n\n---\n\n**One question to close with:** How are you feeling about the pacing of this plan — does it feel like the right level of challenge, or are you hoping to push a little more in certain areas? I want to make sure this feels like *your* plan, not just a template."
        }
